<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<handout>
<title>Daily Prep 1.4 - Linear Equations and the Integrating Factor</title>

<section>
    <title>Overview</title>

  <p>
   This section introduces first-order <term>linear differential equations</term> of the form 
   <m>y' + p(x)\,y = f(x)</m> and develops the <term>integrating factor method</term> for 
   solving them. By multiplying the equation by a specially chosen function <m>r(x)</m>, 
   the left-hand side becomes the derivative of a product, allowing the equation to be 
   integrated directly. The integrating factor turns out to be <m>r(x) = e^{\int p(x)\,dx}</m>, 
   and this method provides a systematic way to solve any linear first-order ODE, leading to an 
   explicit formula for the solution when the required integrals can be computed.
  </p>
</section>

<section>
  <title>Basic learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          These are the tasks you should be able to perform with reasonable
          fluency when you arrive at our next class meeting.
          Important new
          vocabulary words are indicated <em>in italics</em>.
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
     Recognize when an equation is a first-order linear ODE of the form <m>y' + p(x)\,y = f(x)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

<li>
<p>
Understand the purpose of an integrating factor <m>r(x)</m> and how it is used to rewrite the equation as the derivative of a product.
</p>
</li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Apply the integrating factor method to obtain a solvable integrated equation.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

</section>

