<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise label="mcq-intfactor-2">
  <title>The Integrating Factor</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      For the linear ODE  
      <m>y' + 4y = e^{-x}</m>,  
      what is the integrating factor?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\mu(x) = e^{\int 4\,dx} = e^{4x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The integrating factor is 
          <m>\mu(x) = e^{\int p(x)dx}</m>. Here <m>p(x)=4</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\mu(x) = e^{-4x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect sign in the exponent.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\mu(x) = 4e^{x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Not of the correct exponential form <m>e^{\int p(x)dx}</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-intfactor-3">
  <title>Solving a Linear ODE</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the ODE  
      <m>y' + 2y = 6</m>.  
      What is the general solution?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y = 3 + Ce^{-2x}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. With <m>p(x)=2</m>, the integrating factor is <m>e^{2x}</m>.  
          Multiply to get <m>\frac{d}{dx}(e^{2x}y)=6e^{2x}</m>;  
          integrate to obtain <m>e^{2x}y = 3e^{2x} + C</m>,  
          giving <m>y = 3 + Ce^{-2x}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 6 + Ce^{-2x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect steady‑state value; check the integral of <m>6e^{2x}</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = Ce^{2x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Misses the particular solution term.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-intfactor-4">
  <title>Solving an IVP</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the IVP  
      <m>y' - y = e^{x}, y(0)=2.</m>  
      What is <m>y(x)</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y = e^{x}(x+2)</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Write the ODE as <m>y' + (-1)y = e^{x}</m>,  
          so <m>p(x)=-1</m> and <m>\mu(x)=e^{\int -1\,dx}=e^{-x}</m>.  
          Multiply through to obtain <m>\frac{d}{dx}(e^{-x}y)=1</m>,  
          integrate to get <m>e^{-x}y = x + C</m>, and use <m>y(0)=2</m>  
          to find <m>C=2</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = e^{x}(x+1)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This choice uses an incorrect constant.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = 2e^{-x} + e^{x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This does not satisfy the ODE; recompute the integrating‑factor step.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise label="mcq-intfactor-5">
  <title>Understanding the Integrating Factor Method</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Why do we multiply both sides of <m>y' + p(x)y = f(x)</m> by the integrating factor 
      <m>\mu(x)=e^{\int p(x)\,dx}</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>Because it turns the left-hand side into <m>\frac{d}{dx}(\mu(x)y)</m>, making the equation directly integrable.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The integrating factor is chosen so that  
          <m>\mu(x)y' + \mu(x)p(x)y = \frac{d}{dx}(\mu y)</m>,  
          enabling immediate integration.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Because it eliminates <m>f(x)</m> from the equation.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—<m>f(x)</m> remains on the right-hand side.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>Because it ensures the solution will always be exponential.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—only the integrating factor itself is exponential.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="intfactor-concept-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      There is a “trick” to solving linear first-order differential equations described in this 
      section that involves multiplying by a function <m>r(x)</m>.  
      What differentiation rule lies at the heart of this trick?  
      [Hint: It is not the power rule.]
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The trick relies on the <em>product rule</em>:
    </p>
    <me>
      \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(r(x)\,y(x)\bigr)
      = r(x)\,y'(x) + r'(x)\,y(x).
    </me>

    <p>
      We use this identity to rewrite the left-hand side of a linear equation
      <m>y' + p(x)y = f(x)</m> as the derivative of a product after multiplying by the 
      integrating factor <m>r(x)</m>.  The key idea is to choose <m>r(x)</m> so that 
      <m>r'(x) = p(x) r(x)</m>, causing the left-hand side to collapse into a single derivative.  
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>



<exercise xml:id="intfactor-concept-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      In 
      <url href="https://web.uvic.ca/~tbazett/diffyqs/intfactor_section.html#example-18">
        Example 1.4.1
      </url>, 
      <m>p(x)=2x</m>.  Note that 
      <m>\int p(x)\,dx = \int 2x\,dx = x^{2} + C</m>.  
      However, the text simply writes 
      <m>r(x)=e^{\int p(x)\,dx}=e^{x^{2}}</m> and does not include the constant <m>C</m>.  
      Why is this not necessary?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      Because adding a constant <m>C</m> to the exponent simply multiplies the integrating 
      factor by a nonzero constant:
    </p>

    <me>
      e^{\,x^{2} + C} = e^{C}\, e^{x^{2}}.
    </me>

    <p>
      Multiplying the entire linear equation by a nonzero constant does not change the set 
      of solutions, since that factor cancels when solving for <m>y</m>.  
      Therefore, any constant of integration is irrelevant in the integrating factor.  
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>



<exercise xml:id="intfactor-derivation">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Multiply 
      <me>y' + p(x)\,y = q(x)</me>
      on both sides by a function <m>I(x)</m>.
    </p>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p>What is the left-hand side?</p></li>
      <li><p>Compute <m>\bigl[I(x)\,y(x)\bigr]'</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>How should <m>I(x)</m> be chosen so that (a) and (b) are always equal?  That is, what differential equation must it satisfy?</p></li>
      <li><p>Solve <m>\dfrac{dI}{dx} = I(x)\,p(x)</m> for <m>I(x)</m> using separation of variables.</p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <ol marker="(a)">

      <li>
        <p>
          Multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>I(x)</m> gives the left-hand side
        </p>
        <me>
          I(x)\,y' + I(x)\,p(x)\,y.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Using the product rule,
        </p>
        <me>
          \bigl[I(x)\,y(x)\bigr]'
          = I(x)\,y'(x) + I'(x)\,y(x).
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          For the expressions in (a) and (b) to match for all <m>y</m>, we need
        </p>

        <me>
          I'(x)\,y(x) = I(x)\,p(x)\,y(x),
        </me>

        <p>
          which simplifies (assuming <m>I(x)\neq 0</m>) to the differential equation
        </p>

        <me>
          I'(x) = p(x)\,I(x).
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Solve the differential equation using separation of variables:
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac{dI}{I} = p(x)\,dx.
        </me>

        <p>Integrate both sides:</p>

        <me>
          \ln|I| = \int p(x)\,dx + C.
        </me>

        <p>Exponentiate:</p>

        <me>
          I(x) = e^{\int p(x)\,dx + C}
               = e^{C}\, e^{\int p(x)\,dx}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Since <m>e^{C}</m> is a nonzero constant and irrelevant to the method, we write the 
          integrating factor simply as
        </p>

        <me>
          I(x) = e^{\int p(x)\,dx}.
        </me>

      </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
</exercise>



<exercise xml:id="intfactor-IVP">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Here we solve the initial value problem
      <me>
        \frac{dy}{dx} - y = \frac{11}{8}e^{-x/3}, y(0) = -1.
      </me>
    </p>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p>Identify the integrating factor <m>I(x)</m>.</p></li>
      <li><p>
        After multiplying both sides by <m>I(x)</m>, the left-hand side can be written as  
        <m>\dfrac{d}{dx}\bigl( ? \bigr)</m>.  
        What expression belongs inside the parentheses?
      </p></li>
      <li><p>Find the general solution <m>y(x)</m>.</p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li>
        <p>
          Rewrite the ODE as <m>y' + (-1)y = \frac{11}{8}e^{-x/3}</m>, so <m>p(x) = -1</m>.  
          The integrating factor is:
        </p>
        <me>
          I(x) = e^{\int -1\,dx} = e^{-x}.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Multiplying the ODE by <m>I(x)=e^{-x}</m> gives
        </p>

        <me>
          e^{-x}y' - e^{-x}y.
        </me>

        <p>
          By Section 1.4’s product‑rule identity, this equals
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(e^{-x}y\bigr).
        </me>

        <p>
          So the missing expression is <m>e^{-x}y</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The equation becomes
        </p>
        <me>
          \frac{d}{dx}\bigl(e^{-x}y\bigr)
            = \frac{11}{8} e^{-x} e^{-x/3}
            = \frac{11}{8} e^{-4x/3}.
        </me>

        <p>Integrate both sides:</p>

        <md>
          <mrow> e^{-x}y
          \amp = \frac{11}{8} \int e^{-4x/3}\,dx + C </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \frac{11}{8}\left(-\frac{3}{4} e^{-4x/3}\right) + C </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = -\frac{33}{32} e^{-4x/3} + C. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>Multiply by <m>e^{x}</m>:</p>

        <me>
          y
          = -\frac{33}{32}e^{x}e^{-4x/3} + C e^{x}
          = -\frac{33}{32}e^{-x/3} + C e^{x}.
        </me>

        <p>Apply the initial condition <m>y(0)=-1</m>:</p>

        <me>
          -1 = -\frac{33}{32} + C \quad\Longrightarrow\quad C = \frac{1}{32}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Therefore, the specific solution is
        </p>

        <me> y(x)
          = -\frac{33}{32}e^{-x/3}
            + \frac{1}{32} e^{x}.
        </me>
      </li>

    </ol>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="nitric-acid-tank">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A nitric acid solution flows at a constant rate of 6 L/min into a large tank that 
      initially held 200 L of a 0.5% nitric acid solution.  
      The solution inside the tank remains stirred and flows out at a rate of 8 L/min.  
      If the solution entering the tank is 20% nitric acid, determine the volume 
      <m>V(t)</m> of nitric acid in the tank after <m>t</m> minutes.
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="BrineTank1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>Nitric acid in a tank.</caption>
      <image source="BrineTank1.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>
          Diagram of a mixing tank showing a 20% acid solution entering at 
          6 L/min, and a mixed solution leaving at 8 L/min. Inside the tank, 
          <m>V(t)</m> is the amount of nitric acid, and 
          the initial condition is <m>V(0)=1</m> liter.
        </description>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Initially,
      <m>V(0) = 0.005 \cdot 200\ \mathrm{L} = 1\ \mathrm{L}.</m>  
      The tank volume decreases because more flows out than in:
      <m>200 - 2t</m> liters after <m>t</m> minutes.  
      The differential equation is
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{dV}{dt}
      = 1.2 \;-\; \frac{4}{100 - t}\,V.
    </me>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li>
        <p>
          Show that the solution to the IVP  
          <me>
            \frac{dV}{dt} = 1.2 - \frac{4}{100-t}\,V, \qquad V(0)=1,
          </me>
          obtained using an integrating factor, is
          <me>
            V(t)
            = 0.4(100 - t)
              \;-\;
              \frac{39}{100^{4}}(100 - t)^{4}.
          </me>
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          After how many minutes <m>T</m> is the tank empty?
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Since the tank empties at time <m>T</m>, one expects <m>V(T)=0</m> and that the 
          model is valid for <m>0 \le t \le T</m>.  
          Does the graph of <m>V(t)</m> support this?
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <ol marker="(a)">

      <!-- PART (a) -->
      <li>
        <p>
          Rewrite the ODE in linear form:
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac{dV}{dt} + \frac{4}{100 - t}V = 1.2.
        </me>

        <p>
          The integrating factor is
        </p>

        <md>
          <mrow> I(t)
          \amp = \exp\!\left(\int \frac{4}{100 - t}\,dt\right) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = \exp\!\left(-4\ln(100 - t)\right) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = (100 - t)^{-4}. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>
          Multiply both sides of the ODE by <m>(100 - t)^{-4}</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          (100 - t)^{-4}\frac{dV}{dt}
          + (100 - t)^{-5}(-4)V
          = 1.2(100 - t)^{-4}.
        </me>

        <p>
          The left-hand side is the derivative of the product:
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac{d}{dt}\!\left( (100 - t)^{-4} V \right)
          = 1.2(100 - t)^{-4}.
        </me>

        <p>Integrate both sides:</p>

        <me>
          (100 - t)^{-4} V
          =
          \int 1.2(100 - t)^{-4}\,dt + C.
        </me>

        <p>
          Let <m>u = 100 - t</m>, so <m>du = -dt</m>. Then
        </p>

        <md>
          <mrow> \int 1.2(100 - t)^{-4}\,dt 
          \amp = -1.2\int u^{-4}\,du </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = -1.2\left(\frac{u^{-3}}{-3}\right) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = 0.4\,u^{-3} </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = 0.4(100 - t)^{-3}. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>
          Hence:
        </p>

        <me>
          (100 - t)^{-4} V
            = 0.4(100 - t)^{-3} + C.
        </me>

        <p>
          Multiply both sides by <m>(100 - t)^{4}</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          V(t)
          = 0.4(100 - t)
            + C(100 - t)^{4}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Apply <m>V(0) = 1</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          1
          = 0.4(100)
            + C(100)^{4}
          = 40 + C\cdot 100^{4}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Therefore,
        </p>

        <me>
          C = -\frac{39}{100^{4}}.
        </me>

        <p>
          The solution is thus
        </p>

        <me>
          V(t)
          = 0.4(100 - t)
            \;-\;
            \frac{39}{100^{4}}(100 - t)^{4}.
        </me>
      </li>


      <!-- PART (b) -->
      <li>
        <p>
          The tank is empty when its total volume becomes zero.  
          Since the tank starts with 200 L and loses 2 L/min (because outflow is 8 L/min and 
          inflow is 6 L/min), we solve:
        </p>

        <me>
          200 - 2T = 0 \Longrightarrow T = 100\ \text{minutes}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Thus the tank becomes empty after <m>T = 100</m> minutes.
        </p>
      </li>


      <!-- PART (c) -->
      <li>
        <p>
          Evaluate <m>V(t)</m> at <m>t=100</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          V(100)
          = 0.4(100 - 100)
            - \frac{39}{100^{4}}(100 - 100)^{4}
          = 0,
        </me>

        <p>
          as expected.  
          On the interval <m>0 \le t \le 100</m>, the expression
          <m>100 - t</m> remains nonnegative, so the graph of <m>V(t)</m> looks physically 
          reasonable: it starts at <m>V(0)=1</m>, rises initially (since the inflow is very 
          concentrated relative to tank volume), and eventually decreases as the tank drains.  
          The graph approaches 0 smoothly as <m>t\to 100</m>.  
          The behavior is fully consistent with the mixing model.
        </p>
      </li>

    </ol>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="tank-mixing-changing-volume">
  <statement>
    <p>
      At noon, a tank contains 100 L of solution in which 10 kg of chemical is dissolved.  
      Solution containing 2 kg of the chemical per liter flows into the tank at 
      5 L/min.  
      The mixture is well-stirred and drawn off at a rate of 4 L/min.  
      If the tank holds 500 L, when does it overflow?  
      If <m>t</m> measures minutes after noon, find the mass of chemical 
      <m>x(t)</m> (in kg) in the tank at time <m>t</m>.  
      (Set up and solve a linear initial-value problem.)
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <p><strong>Step 1. Tank volume.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Inflow is 5 L/min, outflow is 4 L/min, so volume increases at  
      <m>1\ \mathrm{L/min}</m>.
    </p>

    <me>
      V(t) = 100 + t.
    </me>

    <p>
      The tank overflows when <m>V(t)=500</m>:
    </p>

    <me>
      100 + t = 500 \quad\Longrightarrow\quad t = 400\ \text{minutes}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Step 2. Differential equation for mass of chemical.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Chemical entering: <m>(2\ \mathrm{kg/L})(5\ \mathrm{L/min}) = 10\ \mathrm{kg/min}</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Chemical leaving: concentration in tank is <m>x(t)/V(t)</m>, so  
      outflow chemical rate is
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{x(t)}{100+t}\,(4\ \mathrm{L/min}).
    </me>

    <p>
      Therefore,
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{dx}{dt}
      = 10 \;-\; \frac{4}{100+t}\,x(t),
      \qquad
      x(0)=10.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Step 3. Solve the linear ODE using an integrating factor.</strong></p>

    <p>
      Write in standard form:
    </p>

    <me>
      x' + \frac{4}{100+t}x = 10.
    </me>

    <p>
      Integrating factor:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow> \mu(t)
      \amp = \exp\!\left(\int \frac{4}{100+t}\,dt\right) </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = (100+t)^{4}. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Multiply the ODE by <m>(100+t)^{4}</m>:</p>

    <me>
      \frac{d}{dt}\!\bigl((100+t)^{4} x\bigr)
      = 10(100+t)^{4}.
    </me>

    <p>Integrate:</p>

    <md>
      <mrow> (100+t)^{4} x
      \amp = 10\int (100+t)^{4}\,dt + C </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 10\left(\frac{(100+t)^{5}}{5}\right) + C </mrow>
      <mrow> \amp = 2(100+t)^{5} + C. </mrow>
    </md>

    <p>Divide by <m>(100+t)^{4}</m>:</p>

    <me>
      x(t)
      = 2(100+t) + C(100+t)^{-4}.
    </me>

    <p>Use <m>x(0)=10</m>:</p>

    <me>
      10 = 200 + C(100)^{-4}
      \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
      C = -190\cdot 100^{4}.
    </me>

    <p>Final expression:</p>

    <me>
      x(t)
      = 2(100+t)
        \;-\;
        190\left(\frac{100}{100+t}\right)^{4}.
    </me>

    <p><strong>Answer summary:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>The tank overflows at <m>t=400</m> minutes after noon.</li>
      <li>The mass of chemical is 
        <m>
          x(t)
          =
          2(100+t)
          -190\left(\frac{100}{100+t}\right)^{4}.
        </m>
      </li>
    </ul>

  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="salt-filtering-tank">
  <statement>
    <p>
      A tank initially contains 200 gallons of pure water.  
      Saltwater with concentration 3 ounces of salt per gallon enters at  
      <m>\tfrac12</m> gallon per minute.  
      The mixture drains at the same rate.  
      Additionally, a filtering device removes half the salt contained in 
      <em>one gallon</em> of the mixture per minute.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>y(t)</m> be the number of ounces of salt in the tank at time <m>t</m> minutes.
    </p>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p>Find the initial-value problem (IVP) modeling this situation.</p></li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Use technology to sketch a slope field 
          (<m>-200 \le t \le 1440,\; -80 \le y \le 800</m>).  
          Do any equilibrium solutions appear?  If so, where?
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>Solve the IVP for <m>y(t)</m>.  Plot <m>y(t)</m> for the first 24 hours.</p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>Compute <m>\displaystyle \lim_{t\to\infty} y(t)</m>.</p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>

    <ol marker="(a)">

      <li>
        <p><strong>Modeling the IVP.</strong></p>

        <p>
          Inflow salt rate:
        </p>
        <me>
          (3\ \mathrm{oz/gal})(\tfrac12\ \mathrm{gal/min})
          = 1.5\ \mathrm{oz/min}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Outflow salt rate:
          volume stays 200 gallons,
          so concentration is <m>y/200</m>, and outflow rate <m>\tfrac12</m> gal/min gives
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac{y}{200}\cdot \tfrac12 
          = \frac{y}{400}\ \mathrm{oz/min}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Filtering device removes “half the salt in one gallon per minute”:
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac12\cdot \frac{y}{200}
          = \frac{y}{400}\ \mathrm{oz/min}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Total removal rate is 
          <m>y/400 + y/400 = y/200</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Therefore, the initial-value problem is
        </p>

        <me>
          \frac{dy}{dt}
          = 1.5 - \frac{y}{200},
          \qquad
          y(0)=0.
        </me>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>Equilibrium solution.</strong></p>

        <p>
          Set <m>y'=0</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          1.5 - \frac{y}{200} = 0
          \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
          y = 300.
        </me>

        <p>
          Thus an equilibrium appears at <m>y=300</m> ounces.  
          The slope field (using any technology) will show horizontal segments near <m>y=300</m>.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>Solve the IVP.</strong></p>

        <p>
          Rewrite:
        </p>
        <me>
          y' + \frac{1}{200}y = 1.5.
        </me>

        <p>Integrating factor:</p>

        <me>
          \mu(t) = e^{t/200}.
        </me>

        <p>Multiply through:</p>

        <me>
          \frac{d}{dt}\!\bigl(e^{t/200} y\bigr)
          = 1.5 e^{t/200}.
        </me>

        <p>Integrate:</p>

        <md>
          <mrow> e^{t/200} y
          \amp = 1.5(200)\,e^{t/200} + C </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = 300 e^{t/200} + C. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>Divide by <m>e^{t/200}</m>:</p>

        <me>
          y(t) = 300 + C e^{-t/200}.
        </me>

        <p>Use <m>y(0)=0</m>:</p>

        <me>
          0 = 300 + C
          \quad\Longrightarrow\quad C=-300.
        </me>

        <p>
          Final expression:
        </p>

        <me>
          y(t) = 300\bigl(1 - e^{-t/200}\bigr).
        </me>

        <p>
          A 24‑hour plot (over <m>0 \le t \le 1440</m>) shows a rising curve approaching 300.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p><strong>Long-term behavior.</strong></p>

        <p>
          Compute the limit:
        </p>

        <md>
          <mrow> \lim_{t\to\infty} y(t)
          \amp = 300\left(1 - \lim_{t\to\infty} e^{-t/200}\right) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = 300. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>
          The amount of salt approaches the equilibrium value 300 ounces.
        </p>
      </li>

    </ol>

  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

      <section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives14">
        <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

        <p>
          In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
     Derive the integrating factor <m>r(x) = e^{\int p(x)\,dx}</m> by requiring that the left-hand side become a product derivative.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
     Solve linear ODEs explicitly and check solutions using differentiation, including solutions involving initial conditions. 
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
      Explain why the constant of integration inside the integrating factor does not affect the final solution.
            </p>
          </li>

        </ul>

      </section>


</handout>